title: For Sale:  1862 Enfield Snider
postcontent:
The 1862 dated Enfield is slightly bastardized in that it has three phillps head screws, but they are still brass screws.   It's a 3 band rifle, but missing one band.  The cleaning rod is also wrong.  Someone stuck an 1860's Springfield style-cleaning rod into it.  Reproduction?  I don't know.
 
The barrel is the correct 39 inches long. There is no mount for a bayonet on the barrel. One screw from the Snider brench appears to be missing.  Some odd things about this rifle that made looking up its history rather difficult.  There are no markings on the brass butt plate.  No markings on the brass trigger guard.  No W.D. markings. No markings on the wood stock. Also, another odd feature is there the rear sight is gone. I can’t find any milling marks on the barrel to indicate whether it was broken or intentionally removed. The 1853 Enfield prior to the Snider conversion had a rear sight. So was this done on purpose after the conversion, or someone half assed it? I don’t know.

title: For Sale:  British Muzzleloading Shotgun made by Theophilus Murcott
postcontent:
The labeling on the trigger plate is T. Murcott 68 Haymarket London.  The trigger plate was made by Theophilus Murcott.  The plate is a converted flintlock trigger plate to a precussion cap.  The breach was also converted from a flint lock style to the precussion cap.  The plate is likely 1840-1850's of manufacture. Making the trigger plate over 160 years old itself.
Between 1860-1878 there was a man named Theophilus Murcott that had a gunsmith shop at that location. It is also the same address for W W Greener sportsman firearms that occupied the location at the same time frame. However, W.W. Greener still exists at 68 Haymarket in London to this day.
 
Furthermore, Theophilus Murcott was the man that in 1871 designed and patented the first successfully mass produced hammerless shotgun. A design still used to this day in modern hammerless shotguns. This shotgun is likely one of his “Rookie” or “Novice” made shotguns. Possibly made in 1861 when he first started his business in London.
 
There’s very little fine detailing done to this shotgun. I can find some detailing on the trigger guard and on the back behind the trigger. The wood shows signs of having been sanded down near the butt plate. Unknown why. Seeing as how basic the design is with a lack of any fine details I’d say this was a base model shotgun in the shop.
 
The ramrod for loading is missing. Someone replaced the front steel band with a copper band likely while it was in a muslim country such as Turkey or Afghanistan. The hatching on the trigger is well worn. At 156 years old it’s been through many hands.
 
There are two holes, one on top and one on bottom of the muzzle. No idea why. Don’t know if that’s original or modified. Barrel measures almost 43 inches long. The barrel itself was made by wrapping a long steel band around a bar and turning it into a barrel.  Definantly original style of making a gun barrel.  Sorry but I will not take offer's less than $100. It's worth up to $120 as a rather unique wallhanger.  Buyer pays shipping.
